ls/software if preferred.\n\n---\n\n### Week 2: Combinations and Inverse Functions (Unit 1: Sections 1.5 and 1.6)\n\n**Topics:** \n- Combinations of functions (sum, difference, product, quotient)  \n- Inverse functions  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Using the \"1.5 Combinations of Functions\" and \"1.6 Inverse Functions\" presentations, practice computing combinations of given functions.  \n2. Determine whether functions are invertible using the horizontal line test.  \n3. Find the inverse of simple functions algebraically and verify by composition.  \n4. Create a tutorial video or step-by-step written guide explaining how to find the inverse of a function.  \n\n**Grading Rubric:**  \n- Correct computation of function combinations (30%)  \n- Accurate identification of invertible functions (20%)  \n- Correct finding and verification of inverses (30%)  \n- Clarity and completeness of tutorial/explanation (20%)  \n\n**Adaptations:** Creating a tutorial addresses different modalities. You may opt for a video, slideshow, or written guide.\n\n---\n\n### Week 3: Quadratic Functions and Polynomial Functions (Unit 2: Sections 2.1, 2.2, 2.3)\n\n**Topics:**  \n- Quadratic functions and their graphs  \n- Polynomial functions of higher degree  \n- Finding zeros of polynomials  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Examine the \"2.1 Quadratic Functions,\" \"2.2 Polynomial Functions of Higher Degree,\" and \"2.3 Zeros of Polynomials\" files.  \n2. Graph quadratic and polynomial functions using intercepts and end behavior.  \n3. Find zeros using factoring and synthetic division.  \n4. Solve word problems involving polynomial models.  \n5. Submit completed problem sets with explanations for how you found zeros and graphed functions.  \n\n**Grading Rubric:**  \n- Accuracy of zeros and factorization (35%)  \n- Correct and neat graphs (30%)  \n- Application and explanation in word problems (25%)  \n- Completeness of problem set (10%)  \n\n**Adaptations:** Emphasize graphical visualization and written explanation to support abstract understanding.\n\n---\n\n### Week 4: Trigonometry Basics \u2013 Radians, Unit Circle, and Right Triangle Trig (Unit 4)\n\n**Topics:**  \n- Converting degrees and radians  \n- Understanding the Unit Circle  \n- Basic trig ratios in right triangles  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Study the \"4.1 Radian & Degree,\" \"4.2 The Unit Circle,\" and \"4.3 Right Triangle Trig\" presentations.  \n2. Practice converting between degrees and radians.  \n3. Identify coordinates of key angles on the unit circle.  \n4. Solve problems involving sine, cosine, and tangent in right triangles.  \n5. Draw and label a unit circle with angles in degrees and radians, identifying sine and cosine for those angles.  \n\n**Grading Rubric:**  \n- Accuracy of degree-radian conversions (25%)  \n- Correct unit circle angle identification and coordinates (35%)  \n- Solutions to right triangle trig problems (30%)  \n- Clarity and completeness of unit circle drawing (10%)  \n\n**Adaptations:** Use visual aids and plotting to enhance spatial understanding; physical drawing encouraged.\n\n---\n\n### Week 5: Trigonometric Functions of Any Angle and Graphs of Sine and Cosine (Unit 4: Sections 4.4 and 4.5)\n\n**Topics:**  \n- Understanding trig functions for all angles  \n- Graphs of sine and cosine functions  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Review \"4.4 Trig Functions of Any Angle\" and \"4.5 Graphs of Sine and Cosine\" slides.  \n2. Solve practice problems evaluating trig functions at various angles.  \n3. Sketch sine and cosine graphs, noting amplitude, period, and phase shift.  \n4. Create a visual presentation showing how the graph changes with different parameters (e.g., amplitude, period).  \n\n**Grading Rubric:**  \n- Evaluations of trig functions (30%)  \n- Accuracy and labeling of graphs (35%)  \n- Presentation clarity and demonstration of parameter changes (35%)  \n\n**Adaptations:** Encourages visual and kinesthetic learning by sketching and creating presentations.\n\n---\n\n### Week 6: Using Identities and Verifying Identities (Unit 5)\n\n**Topics:**  \n- Basic trig identities  \n- Verifying identities algebraically  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Study \"5.1 Using Identities\" and \"5.2 Verifying Identities.\"  \n2. Practice simplifying trig expressions using identities.  \n3. Attempt to verify selected identities provided.  \n4. Submit detailed steps showing each simplification and verification.  \n\n**Grading Rubric:**  \n- Correct application of identities (40%)  \n- Logical flow and clear steps in verification (40%)  \n- Presentation and neatness (20%)  \n\n**Adaptations:** Written step-by-step process aids logical thinkers; use colors or highlighting to mark key steps.\n\n---\n\n### Week 7: Law of Sines, Law of Cosines, and Vectors (Unit 6)\n\n**Topics:**  \n- Law of Sines and Cosines for solving triangles  \n- Introduction to vectors  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Review \"6.1 Law of Sines,\" \"6.2 Law of Cosines,\" and \"6.3 Vectors\" materials.  \n2. Solve triangle problems using these laws.  \n3. Practice representing vectors graphically and in component form.  \n4. Write a summary explaining when to use Law of Sines vs. Law of Cosines.  \n\n**Grading Rubric:**  \n- Accuracy of triangle problem solutions (40%)  \n- Correct vector representation and notation (30%)  \n- Quality and clarity of written summary (30%)  \n\n**Adaptations:** Combining graphical and written elements supports diverse learners.\n\n---\n\n### Week 8: Matrix Operations and Applications (Unit 7)\n\n**Topics:**  \n- Matrix addition, multiplication  \n- Inverse and determinants of matrices  \n- Applications of matrices  \n\n**Quest Instructions:**  \n1. Use \"7.4 Matrices,\" \"7.5 Matrix Operations,\" and \"7.6 & 7.7 Inverse & Determinant\" to learn operations.  \n2. Complete practice problems involving matrix arithmetic and finding inverses.  \n3. Solve application problems involving systems of equations with matrices